WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:03.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington, D.C.

00:00:03.510 --> 00:00:23.050
[ Silence ]

00:00:23.050 --> 00:00:26.590
&gt;&gt; Well, good afternoon
and welcome to the African

00:00:26.590 --> 00:00:29.940
and Middle East Division
of the Library of Congress.

00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:33.670
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb, chief of
the division, and I'm delighted

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:39.240
to see you all here today for
this very special presentation

00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:43.240
with Dr. Yoel Finkelman,
the Judaic curator

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:47.470
at the National Library
of Israel in Jerusalem.

00:00:47.470 --> 00:00:49.260
As most of you already know,

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:52.470
our division is made
up of three sections.

00:00:52.470 --> 00:00:55.330
The African, the Middle East,
and the Hebraic sections.

00:00:55.330 --> 00:01:00.070
We're responsible for materials
from 78 different countries

00:01:00.070 --> 00:01:03.330
in the Near East, Central
Asia, the Caucuses,

00:01:03.330 --> 00:01:08.120 position:56%
as well as from the entire continent
of Africa, North and Sub-Saharan.

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:14.150 position:56%
And, we are very active in acquiring
and developing our collections,

00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:18.250
briefing our visitors coming from
all the countries of the region,

00:01:18.250 --> 00:01:23.400
organizing programs,
symposia, workshops.

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:27.400
We also invite scholars and experts
who have researched and done work

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:31.450
in our areas of responsibility
to share with us their insights

00:01:31.450 --> 00:01:35.250
and their findings, so that all
of us attending and participating

00:01:35.250 --> 00:01:39.110
in the programs leave
enriched with new information

00:01:39.110 --> 00:01:43.590
and a better understanding
of what the cultures

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:47.290
and the societies are about.

00:01:47.290 --> 00:01:51.050
We are particularly happy to
welcome Dr. Finkelman today,

00:01:51.050 --> 00:01:54.510
because he's a librarian
and shares similar interests

00:01:54.510 --> 00:01:56.840 position:56%
with members of our Hebraic section.

00:01:56.840 --> 00:02:01.190
His presentation today,
entitled from "Bomberg

00:02:01.190 --> 00:02:05.500
to Beit Midrash" discusses
Hebrew printing in Venice,

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:09.530
a topic that complements one
that was discussed last month

00:02:09.530 --> 00:02:13.950 position:56%
at the Low Library Symposium, and we
have members of the Low Library here

00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:17.330
to commemorate 500
years since the founding

00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:19.990
of the Jewish ghetto Venice.

00:02:19.990 --> 00:02:25.130
But, to tell you more our
very own Sharon Horowitz,

00:02:25.130 --> 00:02:27.260
a senior reference librarian here,

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:32.390
in the Hebraic section we introduce
Dr. Finkelman and the program

00:02:32.390 --> 00:02:35.470
after which you will be invited
to see a wonderful display

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:39.780
of rare book related
to the presentation.

00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:44.380
So, Sharon, and thank you.

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:49.170
&gt;&gt; Thank you Mary Jane,
good afternoon.

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:53.740
On behalf of the Hebraic section
let me add my welcome to you all

00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:56.010
to the African and Middle
Eastern Division meeting room.

00:02:56.010 --> 00:02:58.210
Thank you for joining us.

00:02:58.210 --> 00:02:59.790
As you heard I'm Sharon Horowitz,

00:02:59.790 --> 00:03:01.940
a reference librarian
in the Hebraic section.

00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:07.130 position:56%
The Hebraic section marks its
beginnings in 1912, with the receipt

00:03:07.130 --> 00:03:11.410 position:56%
of 10,000 Hebrew books and pamphlets
whose purchase was made possible

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:15.740
by a gift from New York
philanthropist Jacob Schiff.

00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:18.930
From those humble beginnings,
our collections have grown

00:03:18.930 --> 00:03:24.180
to around 250,000 items in Hebrew,
Yiddish, Ladino, Judeo-Persian,

00:03:24.180 --> 00:03:26.570
and other Hebraic script languages,

00:03:26.570 --> 00:03:30.220 position:56%
and also includes an important
collection of books in the languages

00:03:30.220 --> 00:03:33.280
of Ethiopia, Amharic to
Grenya Angez [phonetic].

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:37.020
The section's holdings are
particularly strong in the areas

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:40.330
of Bible and rabbinic, Hebrew
language and literature,

00:03:40.330 --> 00:03:42.920
responsa and Jewish history.

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:46.650 position:56%
Two of our missions in this division
are to publicize our collections

00:03:46.650 --> 00:03:48.860
and to bring people
into the library.

00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:52.530
One way we do that is by holding
lectures and having programs

00:03:52.530 --> 00:03:55.810
