Is this clear?

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:33.840
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:38.590
&gt;&gt; Okay, first, I want to
begin with thanks of my own,

00:05:38.590 --> 00:05:41.770
in particular to Dr. Ann Brenner,

00:05:41.770 --> 00:05:46.020
who's work in making this
event possible is important.

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:53.110 position:56%
And, in particular for her work on
the exhibit in the back of the hall.

00:05:53.110 --> 00:05:59.210 position:56%
The Talmud has rather unpleasant
things to say about people who stand

00:05:59.210 --> 00:06:01.100
in the presence of their teachers

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:05.540
and issue determinant
conclusions on matters of law.

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:09.200
And, fortunately, our topic is
not actually about matters of law,

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:11.100
otherwise it would be very
uncomfortable speaking

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:17.160
about 16th century Italian-Hebrew
printing in Dr. Brenner's presence,

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:22.570
because I feel like an amateur
in the presence of an expert.

00:06:22.570 --> 00:06:26.860
In addition, I wanted
to thank Sharon Horowitz

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:29.660
and Gale Shirazi [assumed spelling]
who really put an enormous amount

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:33.160
of effort to make my visit
here, both for this lecture

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:35.900
and for some professional
meetings, possible.

00:06:35.900 --> 00:06:39.530
Finally, I want to say that I
remember visiting the Library

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:42.970
of Congress as a little kid on
a family vacation to Washington,

00:06:42.970 --> 00:06:45.330
and coming from a family
of bookworms and --

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:50.120
and nerds it was naturally
on our agenda.

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:52.570
And, speaking here as an adult

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:56.350
in a much more official capacity
is really genuinely an honor.

00:06:56.350 --> 00:06:59.160
It's -- it's really
a trip to be here,

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:00.610
if I can be a little less formal.

00:07:00.610 --> 00:07:06.640
I want to talk about a topic that's
really very close to my heart

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:08.180
and comes from the fact that deep

00:07:08.180 --> 00:07:12.980
down I think I'm basically the
Yeshiva boy and that my attachment

00:07:12.980 --> 00:07:14.970
to Jewish texts and my attachment

00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:18.850
to rabbinic learning was
founded in the Beit Midrash.

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:20.910
And, like many people who
spent time in the Beit Midrash,

00:07:20.910 --> 00:07:25.320
you get used to these big tomes of
the Talmud, of the Shulchan Aruch,

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:27.580
the code of Jewish law, of the tour

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:29.510
and another important
code of Jewish law.

00:07:29.510 --> 00:07:34.470
[Inaudible] a Jewish law, and
you can kind of take these things

00:07:34.470 --> 00:07:37.360
for granted, and in
practice, if we think --

00:07:37.360 --> 00:07:40.920
well, also as a kind of
naïve Yeshiva student,

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:43.100
you take this for granted,
you get used to it.

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.000
You also are not aware,
at least I wasn't,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:49.360
of the way in which the physical
materials, what we might call

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:52.880
in more broad terms the
technology of printing,

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:57.290
affects directly what it is that
students do with one another.

00:07:57.290 --> 00:08:00.900
What is the encounter of
the learner, of the student,

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.210
of the participant in
this learning process?

00:08:03.210 --> 00:08:08.310 position:56%
What is the encounter of that person
with the text, with the knowledge

00:08:08.310 --> 00:08:13.450
that is embodied in that
text, with fellow students?

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:16.990
And, as we'll see later on,
with longer arcs of history

00:08:16.990 --> 00:08:20.550
and transnational groups
whose identity

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:23.260
and religious practice
has formed by these texts.

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:27.780 position:56%
And, as I've gotten older, I've
gotten a little prospective on that,

00:08:27.780 --> 00:08:32.540
and I'm hoping that what we can
work on in the next few minutes is

00:08:32.540 --> 00:08:37.290
to talk about how early 16th
century, particularly in Venice,

00:08:37.290 --> 00:08:40.740
was a major stopping
point for the development

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:46.410
of how rabbinic learning has
happened through the ages.

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:49.180
Not that it doesn't have
a prehistory and not

00:08:49.180 --> 00:08:50.610
that there weren't
developments afterwards.

00:08:50.610 --> 00:08:52.090
Finally, I should talk about --

00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:54.970
mention that I'm talking about a
certain subset of rabbinic texts.

00:08:54.970 --> 00:08:59.020
The overwhelming majority of
Hebrew printings do not follow some

00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:01.460
of the patterns we're
going to talk about.

00:09:01.460 --> 00:09:08.110
But, some of the most critical,
seminal, concrete works

00:09:08.110 --> 00:09:13.640
that cemented rabbinic
self-understanding do fit into some

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:15.480
of the patterns we're
going to talk about.

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:17.900
I'm going to start with
something a little bit inter --

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:20.660
actually anachronistic.

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:32.200
And, this was a -- New York's Time
put up a really fascinating article

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:38.680
on -- on noise -- sound and its
relationship to architecture,

00:09:38.680 --> 00:09:42.220
and we're going to hope
that this cooperates.

00:09:42.220 --> 00:09:44.430
Right now, it's not cooperating.

00:09:44.430 --> 00:09:49.630
So, while we're at it
we'll skip over to a video

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:52.380
of a contemporary Beit Midrash.

00:09:52.380 --> 00:09:55.850
Do we have any sound here?

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:02.930
Here we go.

00:10:02.930 --> 00:10:07.270
Contemporary Beit Midrash,
a small Beit Midrash,

00:10:07.270 --> 00:10:14.180
and it is a noisy and loud place.

00:10:14.180 --> 00:10:16.860
We don't have to watch the entire
seven minutes of this video.

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:24.370 position:56%
This is a small suburban environment
-- a small suburban environment,

00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:27.790
the North Miami Beach Kollel.

00:10:27.790 --> 00:10:30.320 position:56%
In Florida you get a sense of noise,

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:33.200
books piled up on one another,
people in conversation.

00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:37.340
The learning occurs through
this kind of conversation.

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:40.790
Now, if we go back --
let me see if I can get

00:10:40.790 --> 00:10:44.290
that New York Times
thing to appear again.

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:45.590
Here we go.

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:53.270
This is a kind of sound
scape of the reading room

00:10:53.270 --> 00:10:56.340 position:56%
in the New York Public Library, and
what the New York Times wants to get

00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:58.050
across is that despite the fact

00:10:58.050 --> 00:11:02.690
that librarians are famous
for their "Be quiet."

00:11:02.690 --> 00:11:05.440
In fact, there's a great deal of
noise, conveniently the cart is

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:08.210
from the Jewish division, so it
ties right into what we're doing.

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:11.250
And, there's actually an
enormous amount of ambient noise

00:11:11.250 --> 00:11:13.370
in what is supposed to
be a quiet environment.

00:11:13.370 --> 00:11:19.740
These are two entirely different
conceptions of what the look

00:11:19.740 --> 00:11:22.530
and feel of a study hall
