00:11:33.170 --> 00:11:36.310
which the New York Times article
gives us the ability to do.

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:39.290
And, the Beit Midrash -- and
this is a small Beit Midrash.

00:11:39.290 --> 00:11:43.580
If you go into the Beit Midrash,
let's say in the Near Yeshiva Shiva

00:11:43.580 --> 00:11:47.030
in Jerusalem or the Lakewood
Yeshiva in New Jersey,

00:11:47.030 --> 00:11:49.820
probably the two largest
Yeshiva's in the world today.

00:11:49.820 --> 00:11:54.900
The Lakewood Yeshiva at the moment
has between 7000 and 8000 students,

00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:59.130 position:56%
the size of a small university and
probably has more students than were

00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:02.260
in Eastern European yeshivas in all

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:05.890
of Eastern Europe at
any given moment.

00:12:05.890 --> 00:12:09.940
You just -- it's just
cacophony it's just noise,

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:13.780
and without being overtly
anachronistic,

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.310
although just being a little bit
anachronistic, I want to claim

00:12:16.310 --> 00:12:19.910
that this is linked to some of
the decisions that were made

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:24.370
in the 16th century in terms
of printing of rabbinic texts.

00:12:24.370 --> 00:12:25.980
I've shown these pictures.

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:28.880
Most of the items that we're going
to talk about are going to come

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:30.460
from the collection of
the National Library.

00:12:30.460 --> 00:12:34.000
We don't have a great collection
of glossed Christian sources.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.850
So, these are kind of -- had I
been a little more put together I

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:40.530
could've taken them from the
Library of Congress collection,

00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:44.510
but these are basically
items that I've kind

00:12:44.510 --> 00:12:49.900
of picked up from the internet.

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:53.600
These are early glossed
Christian Bibles and manuscript

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:55.780
in early printing, and
if you would show this

00:12:55.780 --> 00:12:59.330
to any traditional yeshiva
boy, the first they'd say is,

00:12:59.330 --> 00:13:02.830
"Why is there a page of Talmud
written in Latin characters?"

00:13:02.830 --> 00:13:06.920
And, in fact, this is kind of the
core of what I want to try to talk

00:13:06.920 --> 00:13:10.190
about is this notion of a central
text in the middle surrounded

00:13:10.190 --> 00:13:13.600
by apparatus or surrounded
by commentary

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:16.730
or what has become more
popular term is peritext.

00:13:16.730 --> 00:13:20.270
But, I don't like peritext
in this context as a term,

00:13:20.270 --> 00:13:22.590
because sometimes it's
really difficult to figure

00:13:22.590 --> 00:13:26.400
out what's the text and
what's the peritext,

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:28.650
what's central and what's not.

00:13:28.650 --> 00:13:31.540
And, in fact, this has become --

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:35.820
what's unique in these rabbinic
printings is not necessarily the

00:13:35.820 --> 00:13:38.190
layout per se.

00:13:38.190 --> 00:13:43.180
What's unique is that this layout
became central and was maintained

00:13:43.180 --> 00:13:48.100
for centuries well after these
kinds of glossed Christian bibles

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:52.940
and polyglot bibles and
works of canon law kind

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:54.240
of dropped out of fashion.

00:13:54.240 --> 00:13:56.280
A lawyer friend of mine, when
I was discussing this with him,

00:13:56.280 --> 00:14:01.800
told me that there are some basic
works of contemporary law that work

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:07.070
with similar kinds of apparatuses
-- apparati [phonetic] in --

00:14:07.070 --> 00:14:09.790
in law school, but he
didn't send me any example,

00:14:09.790 --> 00:14:12.050
so I don't have them here.

00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:15.100
Now, in fact, if we start
looking at the Jewish sources

00:14:15.100 --> 00:14:20.400
where I feel much more comfortable
talking, the kind of standard form

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:25.340
in manuscript versions, even
of glosses, of commentaries,

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:28.590 position:56%
is going to be in manuscript form --

00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:30.560
a manuscript of the
commentary itself.

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:35.020
Let me take a step back and -- and
introduce what we're talking about.

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:37.900
In traditional rabbinic
study, whether we're talking

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:40.140
about the Bible or whether
we're talking about the Talmud

00:14:40.140 --> 00:14:45.420
or whether we're talking about
codes, you have a central text.

00:14:45.420 --> 00:14:47.250
The text is canonical.

00:14:47.250 --> 00:14:49.840
It's canonical not only in
the sense that it is part

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:52.970
of this larger collection of
works that are deemed holy,

00:14:52.970 --> 00:14:54.850
but it is canonical
in that it had --

00:14:54.850 --> 00:15:00.160
has a particular sacred status that
can often be defined in very clear

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:03.290
and unambiguous, sometimes
legal terms.

00:15:03.290 --> 00:15:07.230
So, the Bible is authoritative
in the Jewish tradition

00:15:07.230 --> 00:15:10.440
as the literal word of
god, and while, in fact,

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:14.610 position:56%
Jewish practices often quite removed
from what the bible describes based

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:17.290
on layers and layers of
rabbinic interpretation,

00:15:17.290 --> 00:15:20.880
its status as canonical is
defined as the almost --

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:25.410 position:56%
the constitutional -- as the deepest
layer of the authoritative text.

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:29.280
The Talmud is -- even the
Talmud itself is layered.

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:33.750
The previous early stratum called
the Mishnah and the later stratum,

00:15:33.750 --> 00:15:38.140
also in two versions the Jerusalem
Talmud and the Babylonian Talmud,

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:40.230
which is itself a commentary
on the Mishnah.

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:43.720
But, both of these have
very formal status.

00:15:43.720 --> 00:15:46.620
The Mishnah, is authoritative.

00:15:46.620 --> 00:15:49.220
The later Rabbis --
the Rabbis identified

00:15:49.220 --> 00:15:53.710 position:56%
as Amu Raheem [phonetic] the authors
of the later Talmud, Babylonian

00:15:53.710 --> 00:15:58.090
and Palestinian Talmud,
do not as a matter

00:15:58.090 --> 00:16:01.620
of formal rule argue
with the Mishnah.

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:02.920
They interpret the Mishnah.

00:16:02.920 --> 00:16:06.140
They often interpret the
Mishnah so creatively as to be

00:16:06.140 --> 00:16:08.440
in practice legislating anew,

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:14.070 position:56%
but formally a leader authority does
not argue with an earlier authority.

00:16:14.070 --> 00:16:16.890
After the closing of the
Babylonian Talmud, for all intents

00:16:16.890 --> 00:16:21.050
and purposes later authorities
do not argue with the Talmud.

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:23.690
They interpret the Talmud,
and they interpret the Talmud,

00:16:23.690 --> 00:16:26.370
and therefore determine
matters of law.

00:16:26.370 --> 00:16:31.060
At some point, we'll talk a
little bit later about this,

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:33.030
[inaudible] which he quite
explicitly states he wants

00:16:33.030 --> 00:16:38.080
to be the final word -- he wants
this to be the authoritative voice

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:40.340
of what everybody has to follow.

00:16:40.340 --> 00:16:42.780
And, the collective Jewish
community with the exception

00:16:42.780 --> 00:16:44.090
of a certain subgroup

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:47.720
of the Ammonite Jewish community
essentially ignores him,

00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:53.000
while the Shulchan Aruch, the
16th century code of Jewish law,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:57.820
gains for itself this status
-- formal status of authority.

00:16:57.820 --> 00:16:59.180
Now, what happens with these works

00:16:59.180 --> 00:17:02.760
of canon is naturally
they are ambiguous,

00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:06.090
because all texts are ambiguous,
but in particular the Talmud --

00:17:06.090 --> 00:17:09.110
the Bible is ambiguous,
because isn't terribly concise.

00:17:09.110 --> 00:17:11.530
And, the Talmud is ambiguous,
because it telegraphs all kinds

00:17:11.530 --> 00:17:16.250
of information and is virtually
incomprehensible on its own

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:18.830
without some kind of commentary.

00:17:18.830 --> 00:17:23.730
And, later codes by virtue of
shrinking much larger material --

00:17:23.730 --> 00:17:28.750
much more expansive material
into a bottom line leave

00:17:28.750 --> 00:17:30.050
out all kinds of details.

00:17:30.050 --> 00:17:34.170
So, here we have ambiguous texts
that are formerly authoritative

00:17:34.170 --> 00:17:38.220
and part of the canon, and
they give rise to commentary.

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:40.540
Now, what do you do
with these commentaries?

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:42.440
How do you visualize them?

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:43.740
How does the student see them?

00:17:43.740 --> 00:17:45.040 position:56%
How do you lay them out on the page?

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:47.220
How do you present
them to the student?

00:17:47.220 --> 00:17:50.730
Now, like all printing
endeavors it's some combination

00:17:50.730 --> 00:17:54.940
of finances, technology,
and culture.

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:56.660
How much can we afford?

00:17:56.660 --> 00:17:58.450
What are we capable to do?

00:17:58.450 --> 00:18:01.390
What does the technology enable
us to do, and culturally,

00:18:01.390 --> 00:18:04.500
what matters to us, and
how does it matter to us?

00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:06.850
Chicken and egg problems here
are going to become complicated,

00:18:06.850 --> 00:18:10.030
but let's look at this,
essentially a random example.

00:18:10.030 --> 00:18:14.940 position:56%
Fifteenth century Italian manuscript
of [inaudible] the Pentateuch,

00:18:14.940 --> 00:18:19.230
Rashi [assumed spelling] the most
important mediaeval commentator,

00:18:19.230 --> 00:18:23.110
probably the most important
Jewish commentator ever --

00:18:23.110 --> 00:18:25.240
his commentary both on the Bible

00:18:25.240 --> 00:18:28.400
and on the Talmud are
absolutely indispensable.

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:31.940 position:56%
And, for all intents and purposes,
certainly in the case of the Talmud,

00:18:31.940 --> 00:18:35.110
less so in the case of the Bible,
but for all intents and purposes,

00:18:35.110 --> 00:18:36.870
if the Talmud is ever printed,

00:18:36.870 --> 00:18:39.240
it is certainly printed
with Rashi's commentary.

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:42.830 position:56%
If the Bible is printed, it is also.

00:18:42.830 --> 00:18:44.850
If it's printed with
any apparatus at all,

00:18:44.850 --> 00:18:46.230
it's with Rashi's commentary,

00:18:46.230 --> 00:18:48.850
but here we have simply
Rashi's commentary

00:18:48.850 --> 00:18:52.460
without the text upon
which it is commenting.

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:57.210
Why? Because, manuscripts are too
expensive to waste time and space

00:18:57.210 --> 00:19:02.170
on anything else, and a patron
who is ordering a manuscript copy

00:19:02.170 --> 00:19:06.830
of Rashi's commentary on something
presumably already owns a --

00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:12.290
a copy of the text upon
which Rashi is commenting.

00:19:12.290 --> 00:19:15.220
Or, at the very least knows
that text by heart or assumes

00:19:15.220 --> 00:19:17.700
that the scholar is going
to know that text by heart.

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:20.710
So, let's save a lot of
money and a lot of resources

00:19:20.710 --> 00:19:25.780
by simply treating the commentary
as if it is a separate volume.

00:19:25.780 --> 00:19:27.430
But, of course, Rashi's commentary

00:19:27.430 --> 00:19:30.810
on the bible cannot be
read cover to cover.

00:19:30.810 --> 00:19:36.430
It can't be done, because it's
really a series of short paragraphs

00:19:36.430 --> 00:19:40.250 position:56%
that are comments on a particular
word or a particular biblical verse,

00:19:40.250 --> 00:19:43.360
and there is no obvious connection
between one line and the other.

00:19:43.360 --> 00:19:46.890
It can only be read as a line
by line commentary on the Bible.

00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:51.290
And, therefore, this book on
its own is virtually useless

00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:53.840
without either knowing
the biblical text by heart

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:57.100
or having a manuscript copy of it.

00:19:57.100 --> 00:20:00.420
Even more dramatically is
Rashi's commentary on the Talmud.

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:05.060
Here, also a 15th century
manuscript.

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:08.330
Rashi's commentary
after its publication

00:20:08.330 --> 00:20:11.960
or after its appearance became
absolutely indispensable.

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:17.560
And -- and [inaudible] has
argued completely convincingly

00:20:17.560 --> 00:20:20.650
that Rashi's commentary
made it possible for people

00:20:20.650 --> 00:20:25.220
to study Talmud independently
by filling in all kinds of gaps

00:20:25.220 --> 00:20:26.520
and understanding what's going on.

00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:28.830
Here, too, we have
simply the commentary.

00:20:28.830 --> 00:20:31.500
It is useless without the Talmud,

00:20:31.500 --> 00:20:34.010
but the Talmud is not
presented here.

00:20:34.010 --> 00:20:37.140
Again, let's save some money.

00:20:37.140 --> 00:20:44.410
If we move to the incunable period,
here we have psalms with Radak,

00:20:44.410 --> 00:20:46.400
Rabbi David Kimchi's commentary,

00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:53.150
an extremely important
commentary here from 1477.

00:20:53.150 --> 00:20:54.850
And, here we get to
play a little bit.

00:20:54.850 --> 00:20:56.700
Notice the page layout.

00:20:56.700 --> 00:21:01.700
We have the text of the Psalms
themselves in block square letters,

00:21:01.700 --> 00:21:03.770
and we have the commentary in,

00:21:03.770 --> 00:21:06.450
what we would call
today, a different font.

00:21:06.450 --> 00:21:09.930
What's the text and what's
the power text, right?

00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:12.520
The Psalms here are not the text.

00:21:12.520 --> 00:21:19.110 position:56%
The text is Kimchi's commentary, and
the psalms are there to enable you

00:21:19.110 --> 00:21:23.590
to study Kimhi's commentary,
because this is a lousy way

00:21:23.590 --> 00:21:27.410
to present the text of the psalms
themselves, because if I wanted

00:21:27.410 --> 00:21:30.710
to recite psalms as a ritual
kind of prayer or if I wanted

00:21:30.710 --> 00:21:34.400
to study psalms as part of biblical
poetry, this is a terrible way

00:21:34.400 --> 00:21:37.770
to do it, because one psalm
of seven or eight verses

00:21:37.770 --> 00:21:40.440
or 15 verses is going to be
laid out on three or four pages.

00:21:40.440 --> 00:21:42.740
And, I have to skip
stuff in the middle

00:21:42.740 --> 00:21:44.790
to read the text of the psalm.

00:21:44.790 --> 00:21:48.000
The -- the text of the
verse is there to enable me

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:51.610
to study the commentary of Kimchi.

00:21:51.610 --> 00:21:55.950
Now, we move forward to
something that starts

00:21:55.950 --> 00:21:57.860
to look a little bit
more like the page layout

00:21:57.860 --> 00:22:00.480
of a standard Talmudic text today.

00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:03.820
Here, a Spanish -- Pentateuch --

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:07.310
commentaries of Rashi and the
ancient Aramaic translation

00:22:07.310 --> 00:22:11.400
of Onkelos beginning
to lay out in columns.

00:22:11.400 --> 00:22:17.180
Looks a little bit more like
a polyglot Bible as well,

00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:19.440
with the text of the
Bible in the middle

00:22:19.440 --> 00:22:21.120
with -- with the vowel markings.

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:30.440
And, here, we start to see
a more interesting interplay

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:33.070 position:56%
between the texts that are laid out.

00:22:33.070 --> 00:22:40.410
So, that's a kind of transition.

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:44.510
Now, we move forward into
Venice in the sixteenth century,

00:22:44.510 --> 00:22:48.880
and we start to see things
that are more complicated.

00:22:48.880 --> 00:22:54.030
Now, part of what's going on here,
as we start to see these kinds

00:22:54.030 --> 00:22:58.380
of texts, is that printing
enables lowering of prices.

00:22:58.380 --> 00:23:01.780
Printing enables much
more of an ability to plan

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:05.300
in advance how you want to lay out
these texts, so that you can fit

00:23:05.300 --> 00:23:08.570
on a page something
quite this complicated.

00:23:08.570 --> 00:23:11.410
There were attempts to do
things like this in manuscript,

00:23:11.410 --> 00:23:15.760
but they weren't able to include
quite as much as what's going

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:21.850
to be included here, and you
have a market that is interested.

00:23:21.850 --> 00:23:26.610
Here, we're looking at the
second edition of Bomberg's --

00:23:26.610 --> 00:23:29.630
Daniel Bomberg's "Mikraot
Gedolot" a rabbinic Bible.

00:23:29.630 --> 00:23:31.840
Certainly will be celebrating
next year the --

00:23:31.840 --> 00:23:38.070
the 500th anniversary of the
first rabbinic Bible in 1517,

00:23:38.070 --> 00:23:43.740
and a copy of the first rabbinic
Bible, the first Mikraot Gedolot is

00:23:43.740 --> 00:23:46.690
in the exhibit space in the back.

00:23:46.690 --> 00:23:52.060
And, it's in the top five of the
most important printing events

00:23:52.060 --> 00:23:54.670
in the history of the Hebrew book.

00:23:54.670 --> 00:23:55.970
We're using the second edition,

00:23:55.970 --> 00:24:00.840
because the second edition is the
one focused more on Jewish readers

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:04.120
than the first edition,
which was more focused --

00:24:04.120 --> 00:24:06.810
again, this is a matter of
degree, not a matter of kind,

00:24:06.810 --> 00:24:10.090
but more focused on
Christian readership.

00:24:10.090 --> 00:24:15.450
And, here what we have -- I don't
know, can you see my -- the arrow?

00:24:15.450 --> 00:24:17.980 position:56%
Okay, we have the text of the Bible.

00:24:17.980 --> 00:24:23.340
We have the Aramaic --
ancient Aramaic translation,

00:24:23.340 --> 00:24:26.250
the commentary of Rashi,
indispensable.

00:24:26.250 --> 00:24:31.620
The commentary of the Spanish
mediaeval exergy Eben Ezra,

00:24:31.620 --> 00:24:36.630
and as well the Masoretic notes.

00:24:36.630 --> 00:24:42.810
The Masoretic notes which had
outside of a small circle of kind

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:47.320
of OCD people who were really
concerned with the exact spelling

00:24:47.320 --> 00:24:50.260
of every last word in
the Masoretic edition

00:24:50.260 --> 00:24:52.400
of the bible had largely
fallen into day

00:24:52.400 --> 00:24:55.060
to day disuse by a typical reader.

00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:58.330
But, in the Mikraot Gedolot

00:24:58.330 --> 00:25:01.370
in Bomberg's rabbinic bible
they were absolutely critical,

00:25:01.370 --> 00:25:04.710
because one of the most important
influences of this publication is

00:25:04.710 --> 00:25:10.090
that it really set the fixed
Masoretic text from then on.

00:25:10.090 --> 00:25:12.280
But, I'm less interested in
the history of the text --

00:25:12.280 --> 00:25:15.020
the Masoretic text of the bible
itself and more interested

00:25:15.020 --> 00:25:19.130
in what we've got going on here,
which is a primary text laid

00:25:19.130 --> 00:25:24.620
out in the middle, multiple
commentaries laid out around,

00:25:24.620 --> 00:25:28.180 position:56%
and what is also going to become
critical -- we'll see more examples.

00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:31.190
The commentaries are
aware of each other.

00:25:31.190 --> 00:25:36.370
That is to say Rashi on this side
of the page comments on the Bible.

00:25:36.370 --> 00:25:41.460
Eben Ezra comments on the Bible,
but also explicitly makes reference

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:43.030
to Rashi's previous commentary.

00:25:43.030 --> 00:25:46.470
So, we have on the
page a conversation,

00:25:46.470 --> 00:25:51.240
a three-way conversation
that's going on.

00:25:51.240 --> 00:25:54.190
Another example -- we can kind
of multiply these examples,

00:25:54.190 --> 00:26:00.500
and we see the way -- Alfasi,
the great north African -- the --

00:26:00.500 --> 00:26:04.350
who's -- who's [inaudible] --
who's work kind of summarizing

00:26:04.350 --> 00:26:10.130
and condensing the Talmud
into its bottom line,

00:26:10.130 --> 00:26:11.860
was often studied as the primary.

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:14.640
There was a while when people were
not quite sure whether the Talmud

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:17.360
was going to become the most
important Jewish rabbinic text

00:26:17.360 --> 00:26:21.810
or Alfasi's was going to
become the major core of study.

00:26:21.810 --> 00:26:30.030
And, here, too, we get -- we get
the central text in the middle,

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:38.030
[inaudible] Eben Habib commentary
on Alfasi, also from Bomberg.

00:26:38.030 --> 00:26:43.330
Now, we're going to talk a little
bit about Talmud, because Talmud is

00:26:43.330 --> 00:26:52.580
in many ways the core -- observant
Jews today are certainly much more

00:26:52.580 --> 00:26:55.280
Jews of the Talmud than
they are of the Bible.

00:26:55.280 --> 00:26:59.430
So, here we have a
1482 incunable edition

00:26:59.430 --> 00:27:02.390
from Spain, [inaudible] Kiddushin.

00:27:02.390 --> 00:27:03.690
Nope -- spelling error there.

00:27:03.690 --> 00:27:06.230
It should say Kiddushin,
not Kiddush.

00:27:06.230 --> 00:27:10.530
And, here, again, you see this
kind of multiple text on the page.

00:27:10.530 --> 00:27:13.020
It's clear that the
Talmud is the core text.

00:27:13.020 --> 00:27:18.420
Rashi's commentary on the outside,
but the standard page of Talmud,

00:27:18.420 --> 00:27:22.330
which we'll get to later
on, had not yet formed.

00:27:22.330 --> 00:27:25.450
But, as we move forward,
some [inaudible] Talmud,

00:27:25.450 --> 00:27:30.280
we also have a volume
of that in the exhibit.

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:32.820
Fifteen -- this is a 1510 edition.

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:38.010
He begins including not only the
Talmud in the middle of the page,

00:27:38.010 --> 00:27:41.060
but Rashi and the commentary
of the Tosephists,

00:27:41.060 --> 00:27:46.200
the Ashkenazi commentaries
on the Talmud.

00:27:46.200 --> 00:27:48.380
Now, let's just skip ahead

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:51.380
to one more page before we talk
a little bit about what's going

00:27:51.380 --> 00:27:55.670
on here in these Talmuds.

00:27:55.670 --> 00:27:59.710
Another typo, it should say 1520.

00:27:59.710 --> 00:28:03.280
This is a Bomberg edition.

00:28:03.280 --> 00:28:05.740
Bomberg -- Daniel Bomberg,
the printer --

00:28:05.740 --> 00:28:08.690
Venice printer is particularly
important,

00:28:08.690 --> 00:28:11.820
probably the most important
printing of the Talmud

00:28:11.820 --> 00:28:15.760
because he was the first to
print the complete edition

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:17.060
of the Babylonian Talmud.

00:28:17.060 --> 00:28:21.190
And, in addition to
that, he also made --

00:28:21.190 --> 00:28:25.100
well, he did two things that
became absolutely critical

00:28:25.100 --> 00:28:26.400
in the future of the Talmud.

00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:29.720
The first is that he
paginated all the pages.

00:28:29.720 --> 00:28:33.880
Not simply paginated them
for his particular edition,

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:35.460
but he was very conscious

00:28:35.460 --> 00:28:40.490
about setting a fixed
pagination for the entire Talmud.

00:28:40.490 --> 00:28:42.500
Only he could do it
because he's the first one

00:28:42.500 --> 00:28:45.250
to ever print the entire thing.

00:28:45.250 --> 00:28:48.440
And, he was conscious of this,
and instead of simply being able

00:28:48.440 --> 00:28:52.880
to reference a page of
Talmud, the third chapter of --

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:56.310
of [inaudible] Kiddushin,
he would be able

00:28:56.310 --> 00:28:58.720
to identify a much
smaller body of text.

00:28:58.720 --> 00:29:03.340
And, you could enable cross
referencing much more easily.

00:29:03.340 --> 00:29:06.220
He was very conscious of this,
and in fact, in further printings

00:29:06.220 --> 00:29:11.670
of commentaries and codes he
would insert page numbers,

00:29:11.670 --> 00:29:19.530 position:56%
references to his own edition of the
Talmud, creating a kind of monopoly.

00:29:19.530 --> 00:29:24.560
It's like, you know, buying Windows
and getting it packaged with --

00:29:24.560 --> 00:29:28.740
with Internet Explorer, except
-- this little bit, I guess,

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:32.650
also anachronistic now, that
unlike your web browser,

00:29:32.650 --> 00:29:34.950
you can pick whatever
web browser you want.

00:29:34.950 --> 00:29:40.000
But, he essentially was able
to create a kind of dependence

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:43.920
on his edition of the Talmud
by printing later editions

00:29:43.920 --> 00:29:46.360
with references to his own edition.

00:29:46.360 --> 00:29:50.960
So -- so that was one
thing that he did.

00:29:50.960 --> 00:29:54.290
The other thing that he did was
that he chose a particular edition

00:29:54.290 --> 00:29:57.790
of the commentary of the
Tosephists to put together

00:29:57.790 --> 00:30:00.050
with the commentary of Rashi.

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:03.130
And, he had to edit a little
bit, and he had to cut things

00:30:03.130 --> 00:30:04.800
down to get it to fit on the page.

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:07.930
And, whether he made a good
decision about which manuscript

00:30:07.930 --> 00:30:11.780
of the Tosephists to use
is a matter of some debate.

00:30:11.780 --> 00:30:15.660
But, it hardly mattered because
once he included that edition

00:30:15.660 --> 00:30:20.040
of the Tosephists commentary on
the page it became the edition

00:30:20.040 --> 00:30:21.410
of the Tosephists commentary.

00:30:21.410 --> 00:30:25.490
Now, we can start talking a little
bit about the content and talk

00:30:25.490 --> 00:30:30.990
about what's going on in
his choice of commentaries.

00:30:30.990 --> 00:30:34.620
First of all, Rashi and the
Tosephists, despite the fact

00:30:34.620 --> 00:30:40.160 position:56%
that they're both Ashkenazi, they're
both French-German world of thought

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:43.290
as opposed to the Spanish
and north African traditions

00:30:43.290 --> 00:30:49.230 position:56%
of interpretation, they actually in
kind represent polar extremes of how

00:30:49.230 --> 00:30:51.130
to go about commenting
on the Talmud.

00:30:51.130 --> 00:30:56.940
The Talmud is a complicated,
dense, obtuse, telegraphic text.

00:30:56.940 --> 00:31:00.600
It is virtually incomprehensible,
certainly today,

00:31:00.600 --> 00:31:04.740
without the commentary of Rashi,
who fills in gaps, explains what --

00:31:04.740 --> 00:31:07.340
questions what cryptic lines means,

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:10.240
fills in background
information, and the like.

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:14.630
His goal is simply to
enable you to read the page.

00:31:14.630 --> 00:31:17.540
Well, simply -- that's not really
fair because he was such a master

00:31:17.540 --> 00:31:20.640
of commentary that in the
process of teaching you how

00:31:20.640 --> 00:31:23.580
to simply read the page and
make sense of the conversation,

00:31:23.580 --> 00:31:28.090
he's actually solving all kinds of
problems you weren't even aware of.

00:31:28.090 --> 00:31:31.100
And, one of the things that
good rabbinic scholars have

00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:34.700 position:56%
to train themselves to do is to then
go back to the text of the Talmud

00:31:34.700 --> 00:31:37.230
and pretend they hadn't read Rashi,

00:31:37.230 --> 00:31:39.690
because how would another
commentary read this

00:31:39.690 --> 00:31:43.880
without already having superimposed
upon me Rashi's assumptions.

00:31:43.880 --> 00:31:49.200
Now, the Tosephists
are worlds apart.

00:31:49.200 --> 00:31:55.710
They did something remarkable,
and they said the Mishnah,

00:31:55.710 --> 00:31:59.780
the earlier stratum of the Talmud,
is a fairly straightforward text.

00:31:59.780 --> 00:32:03.630
The Talmud comes along and
complicates it by assuming, rightly

00:32:03.630 --> 00:32:07.230
or wrongly, that the Mishnah
is a coherent and unified text

00:32:07.230 --> 00:32:08.980
that doesn't contradict itself.

00:32:08.980 --> 00:32:11.770
And, the Talmud comes
along and says --

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:15.340
a later stratum and says the
earlier stratum of the Mishnah --

00:32:15.340 --> 00:32:18.200
let's search -- hunt high and
low for contradictions and try

00:32:18.200 --> 00:32:20.010
to solve those contradictions.

00:32:20.010 --> 00:32:25.570
The Tosephists do the
same thing to the Talmud.

00:32:25.570 --> 00:32:27.270
They assume that the Talmud itself,

00:32:27.270 --> 00:32:29.960
and here at least historically
speaking,

00:32:29.960 --> 00:32:33.420
they're almost certainly
wrong, the Tosephists assume,

00:32:33.420 --> 00:32:37.010
let's do to the Talmud what
the Talmud did to the Mishnah.

00:32:37.010 --> 00:32:38.500
Let's assume that the
Talmud itself --

00:32:38.500 --> 00:32:42.360
the Babylonian Talmud is
itself incoherent text devoid

00:32:42.360 --> 00:32:43.660
of any contradictions.

00:32:43.660 --> 00:32:48.210
Let's look high and low for
any imaginable contradiction

00:32:48.210 --> 00:32:51.060
between any passage in the
Talmud and do all kinds

00:32:51.060 --> 00:32:54.000
of creative interpretation
to solve that.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.930
The result is a reworking
of the Talmud,

00:32:56.930 --> 00:33:01.380
sometimes a reinterpretation,
sometimes an interpretation

00:33:01.380 --> 00:33:03.970
that is radically different than
what appears to be on the page.

00:33:03.970 --> 00:33:06.730
The rule appears to
apply across the board.

00:33:06.730 --> 00:33:08.030
This is the law.

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:10.820
It turns out it's only on
Tuesday afternoon double headers

00:33:10.820 --> 00:33:12.120
with a lefty pitcher.

00:33:12.120 --> 00:33:17.400
Those are the kinds of things
that the Tosephists will do.

00:33:17.400 --> 00:33:20.900
And, so what you get on the
page are not only the text

00:33:20.900 --> 00:33:24.300 position:56%
of the Talmud itself, the simple
straightforward commentary of Rashi,

00:33:24.300 --> 00:33:29.020 position:56%
but the Tosephists that open up this
world of analysis and hyperlink --

00:33:29.020 --> 00:33:32.750
I'm not the first one to notice
this parallel -- the hyperlink --

00:33:32.750 --> 00:33:37.950
the Talmud to itself
and create this dialog.

00:33:37.950 --> 00:33:41.390
Now, so look what happens
in kind of an image

00:33:41.390 --> 00:33:46.350
on the page is we get the
Talmud, which itself branches out

00:33:46.350 --> 00:33:49.280
and create conversations
of the two commentators.

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:54.380
And, again we get to two
commentators talking,

00:33:54.380 --> 00:33:58.070
not quite with each other,
because the standard opening line

00:33:58.070 --> 00:33:59.570
of a paragraph of commentary

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:04.190
by the Tosephists is
perush akuntras [phonetic],

00:34:04.190 --> 00:34:08.590 position:56%
which to oversimplify a little bit,
means this is Rashi's interpretation

00:34:08.590 --> 00:34:11.360
of the Talmudic passage,
that is inevitably followed

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:13.800
up with vikasha [phonetic].

00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:15.100
That's a problem.

00:34:15.100 --> 00:34:17.690
It doesn't work, because if
you interpret this passage

00:34:17.690 --> 00:34:20.340
in the Talmud the way
Rashi wants you to,

00:34:20.340 --> 00:34:22.870
you're going to create a
contradiction with another passage

00:34:22.870 --> 00:34:28.350
in an entirely different volume
that you didn't even remember.

00:34:28.350 --> 00:34:34.250
Now, that's remarkable, probably
Rashi would have said in response.

00:34:34.250 --> 00:34:37.120
I'm not trying to solve
a problem over there.

00:34:37.120 --> 00:34:39.320
I'm just trying to tell you
how to read the page over here

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:41.560
in the simplest possible way.

00:34:41.560 --> 00:34:43.000
Again, this is setting it

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.460
up a little bit more
dichotomous than it actually is.

00:34:46.460 --> 00:34:52.320
But, you create this three-way
conversation on the page.

00:34:52.320 --> 00:34:55.670
Let's stop for second and
think about the experience

00:34:55.670 --> 00:34:59.960
of the student who
opens up this page.

00:34:59.960 --> 00:35:03.850
What are -- we're going to put
on our teacher hats for a second.

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:07.580
And, I'll skip ahead a little
bit to a contemporary work

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:10.840
of academic scholarship,
but let's make explicit --

00:35:10.840 --> 00:35:14.220
the implicit assumptions
that are here on the page.

00:35:14.220 --> 00:35:17.210
The first is, that
there is a central text.

00:35:17.210 --> 00:35:20.840
The central text is the text of
the Talmud with the earlier stratum

00:35:20.840 --> 00:35:24.120
of the Mishnah and the later
strata of the Talmud itself.

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:25.430
That text is authoritative.

00:35:25.430 --> 00:35:27.260
It is in the center.

00:35:27.260 --> 00:35:30.490
It gets the nice woodcut
letters at the top.

00:35:30.490 --> 00:35:33.970
We're not exclusively
for holy texts,

00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:36.860
but they certainly give it
a certain kind of weight.

00:35:36.860 --> 00:35:38.720
That text is central
and authoritative.

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:41.270
Secondly, that text
is not transparent.

00:35:41.270 --> 00:35:46.630
You have to do some
work to understand it.

00:35:46.630 --> 00:35:50.330 position:56%
But, the work that you have to do to
understand it is going to be colored

00:35:50.330 --> 00:35:54.380
by equally canonical commentaries.

00:35:54.380 --> 00:35:57.790
You are not alone in this endeavor
of interpreting the Talmud.

00:35:57.790 --> 00:36:03.920
You are working within an
established canon of commentaries.

00:36:03.920 --> 00:36:09.770
Third, the commentaries themselves
are in conversation with one other.

00:36:09.770 --> 00:36:13.230
They are explicitly in
conversation with one another.

00:36:13.230 --> 00:36:18.300
They are creating this
larger conversation.

00:36:18.300 --> 00:36:23.610
And, fourth, it is the job of
the student sitting with the book

00:36:23.610 --> 00:36:26.220
to put all of this together.

00:36:26.220 --> 00:36:30.990
That, I think, is the single most
important educational philosophy

00:36:30.990 --> 00:36:33.510
implication of this
type of page layout.

00:36:33.510 --> 00:36:35.960
It is -- is this my next slide?

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:40.440
It's not. But, let me go
ahead of myself a second.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:45.400
Here, is where Torskey's [assumed
spelling] introduction to the Code

00:36:45.400 --> 00:36:47.840
of Maimonides [phonetic],
shows in largely random

00:36:47.840 --> 00:36:49.260
because the previous slide,
which we haven't gotten

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:52.310
to yet, is of Maimonides Code.

00:36:52.310 --> 00:36:53.610
What is his assumption?

00:36:53.610 --> 00:36:58.080
I mean, it doesn't have
to be Professor Torskey.

00:36:58.080 --> 00:37:00.100
It could be any other work

00:37:00.100 --> 00:37:03.890 position:56%
of contemporary academic scholarship
laid out with the text on the top

00:37:03.890 --> 00:37:07.810
and footnotes are peritext
on the bottom.

00:37:07.810 --> 00:37:10.450
The assumption is that there is
this older canon of literature,

00:37:10.450 --> 00:37:13.850
that the Code of Maimonides
is a text worth understanding,

00:37:13.850 --> 00:37:16.860
but that it is the
task of the scholar

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:20.240 position:56%
to do the interpretive work for you.

00:37:20.240 --> 00:37:23.130
Now, granted, he is not
an absolute authority,

00:37:23.130 --> 00:37:25.850
despite what many professors
sometimes think.

00:37:25.850 --> 00:37:30.080 position:56%
He has a responsibility to you as
the reader to give you the footnotes

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:33.730
in the apparatus so that you can
go back to the original sources

00:37:33.730 --> 00:37:37.700
and double check and see if you
find his interpretation compelling.

00:37:37.700 --> 00:37:40.830
But, ultimately, he is
doing the synthesis.

00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:43.820
It is the job of the author
of the academic monograph

00:37:43.820 --> 00:37:50.760 position:56%
to do the synthesis for you, as
opposed to, if we go back previously

00:37:50.760 --> 00:37:54.960
to our page here where the
assumption is that it is the job

00:37:54.960 --> 00:37:59.420
of the student to do the
interpretive work him,

00:37:59.420 --> 00:38:01.770
or increasingly, herself.

00:38:03.490 --> 00:38:06.170
Now, what happens in the just --

00:38:06.170 --> 00:38:13.430
Justinian Talmud is in
addition to the Talmud, Rashi,

00:38:13.430 --> 00:38:19.820
and the Tosephists, we
get two other tools.

00:38:19.820 --> 00:38:26.690
We get a set of explicit
hyperlinks of explicit footnotes

00:38:26.690 --> 00:38:32.710
that cross reference to the
Talmud to a set of other works.

00:38:32.710 --> 00:38:36.460
First of all, it cross
references the Talmud to itself.

00:38:36.460 --> 00:38:39.980
Sometimes the Talmud has
passages that appear more or less

00:38:39.980 --> 00:38:42.480
in identical, or at the
very least similar versions,

00:38:42.480 --> 00:38:44.160
in several different places.

00:38:44.160 --> 00:38:45.700
So, if you're learning
the passage here,

00:38:45.700 --> 00:38:47.970
if you're studying the passage
here, you want to know how

00:38:47.970 --> 00:38:50.780
that same passage appears,
if it's in the same text

00:38:50.780 --> 00:38:54.580
or what context it's embedded
in in another track date.

00:38:54.580 --> 00:38:59.690
It cross references the Talmud
to the Biblical verses so that

00:38:59.690 --> 00:39:01.840
if you're studying and
there's a reference to a verse,

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:05.420
you can go back to the
original verse and look it up.

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:08.200
And, finally and most importantly,
and these are the two arrows

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:12.120
that are headed out,
the amishbat [phonetic],

00:39:12.120 --> 00:39:16.950
which cross references the
Talmud to codes of Jewish law,

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:21.350
particularly for our
purposes, Maimonides Code

00:39:21.350 --> 00:39:25.060
and the Tor [inaudible] Ruch,
the two other major code --

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:28.880
well, the two other -- there's
also [inaudible], the large book

00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:32.140
of commandments, which
due to various reasons

00:39:32.140 --> 00:39:35.090
of intellectual history
doesn't maintain its same status

00:39:35.090 --> 00:39:38.250
over the course of the
-- of the centuries.

00:39:38.250 --> 00:39:44.300
And, then you not only have this
kind of triangle of primary text,

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:46.230
commentaries, and conversation
with other -- in --

00:39:46.230 --> 00:39:48.760
in conversation with the student.

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:54.240 position:56%
You have all of that in conversation
with several other volumes,

00:39:54.240 --> 00:40:00.170
all of which can be laid out
in an almost identical fashion.

00:40:00.170 --> 00:40:04.050
And, then the whole thing
becomes incestuous and impossible,

00:40:04.050 --> 00:40:09.690
especially since you might have
a reference to Maimonides Code,

00:40:09.690 --> 00:40:10.990
and you might have a reference

00:40:10.990 --> 00:40:13.350
to Joseph Karo's [assumed
spelling] Shulchan Aruch.

00:40:13.350 --> 00:40:17.300
And, lo and behold, at least in
later editions of Maimonides Code,

00:40:17.300 --> 00:40:20.560
who is one of the major
commentators on Maimonides Code,

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:24.040
the same Joseph Karo who
authored the Shulchan Aruch.

00:40:24.040 --> 00:40:28.290
In other words, the thing
explodes exponentially.

00:40:28.290 --> 00:40:30.370
You don't have a linear
growth in the amount

00:40:30.370 --> 00:40:33.200
of possible commentaries
and super-commentaries.

00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:38.120
You have an exponential growth, and
you have this kind of intricate web

00:40:38.120 --> 00:40:41.230
of possible connections
between different volumes,

00:40:41.230 --> 00:40:45.000
each of which has its own
intricate rabbinic page layout.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:49.750
Just for the sake of the
curiosity, 1616 crack out edition

00:40:49.750 --> 00:40:54.190
of the Talmud reappears with
only the Talmud and Rashi,

00:40:54.190 --> 00:40:56.500
but that is the exception
that proves the rule.

00:40:56.500 --> 00:41:03.260
Since Bomberg, every single
edition with -- I know of three.

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:05.280
No, I know of two exceptions.

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:06.750
Every single edition --

00:41:06.750 --> 00:41:10.560
printed edition of the
Talmud afterwards builds

00:41:10.560 --> 00:41:14.740
on Bombergs adds perhaps.

00:41:14.740 --> 00:41:21.200
But, basically uses Bombergs
format and page layout.

00:41:21.200 --> 00:41:27.760
Similar kind of thing going on
in the two infamous editions

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:33.370
of Maimonides Mishnah Torah,
Maimonides Code of Law from 1551.

00:41:33.370 --> 00:41:35.010
Justinian and Bragadeen
[assumed spelling].

00:41:35.010 --> 00:41:40.130
Not only are these
extremely beautiful volumes,

00:41:40.130 --> 00:41:43.350
at least from my personal
subjective perspective.

00:41:43.350 --> 00:41:47.230
I think the Justinian Maimonides
Mishnah Torah is perhaps the

00:41:47.230 --> 00:41:49.950
beautiful Hebrew printed book ever.

00:41:49.950 --> 00:41:54.110
But, that's just my personal
subjective reaction to it.

00:41:54.110 --> 00:41:57.940
And, the absolute tragedy
that was created

00:41:57.940 --> 00:42:00.550
by these two competing
simultaneous Venice editions

00:42:00.550 --> 00:42:03.250
of the Mishnah Torah --
basically the chief rabbi

00:42:03.250 --> 00:42:08.170
of Paduah [phonetic] had written
a commentary on Maimonides Code

00:42:08.170 --> 00:42:10.190
and wanted to get it published.

00:42:10.190 --> 00:42:13.170
Justinian refused.

00:42:13.170 --> 00:42:14.470
Bragadeen agreed.

00:42:14.470 --> 00:42:18.550 position:56%
It was one of the first publications
that his publishing house published.

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:21.170
When Justinian heard that there
was a competer opening up,

00:42:21.170 --> 00:42:25.620
he quickly grabbed
parts of that commentary

00:42:25.620 --> 00:42:27.860
and quickly issued his own version.

00:42:27.860 --> 00:42:30.000
This got [inaudible] and
Bogen [assumed spelling]

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.810
of Paduah very upset.

00:42:32.810 --> 00:42:36.880
He created a hullabaloo [phonetic],
turned to Rabbi Moses Isserles

00:42:36.880 --> 00:42:40.380
of Crackow, the most important
rabbinic decider of the day,

00:42:40.380 --> 00:42:43.200
and said, "You have to issue a --

00:42:43.200 --> 00:42:46.700
a decree that nobody can buy
the new competing edition,"

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:48.430
which Rabbi Isserles did.

00:42:48.430 --> 00:42:53.730
And, the two Christian printers
eventually turned to the Pope

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:55.200
and said, "You figure this out."

00:42:55.200 --> 00:42:57.580
And, he said, "Well, let's
take a look at what's written

00:42:57.580 --> 00:42:59.320
in all this rabbinic stuff."

00:42:59.320 --> 00:43:02.140
And, that eventually led to
the burning of the Talmud

00:43:02.140 --> 00:43:05.500
and other important
rabbinic books in 1553.

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:08.290
So, you have a kind of sharp
contrast between the beauty

00:43:08.290 --> 00:43:10.590
of these printed volumes
and the tragedy

00:43:10.590 --> 00:43:12.400
that ensued as a result of them.

00:43:12.400 --> 00:43:15.370
But, also you see the
same kind of page layout,

00:43:15.370 --> 00:43:18.610
in some ways even more
elaborate, as well as some

00:43:18.610 --> 00:43:24.880
of the interpretive hyperlink
apparatus along the commentaries.

00:43:24.880 --> 00:43:29.100
Just, you know, the -- the
two other major editions,

00:43:29.100 --> 00:43:30.400 position:56%
which I don't really have time to go

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:31.850
through the whole history
of their printing.

00:43:31.850 --> 00:43:35.600
But, the Fortureem [phonetic] and
the Shulchan Aruch, two major codes

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:39.890
of Jewish law that were originally
printed also in a single text

00:43:39.890 --> 00:43:44.730
in one volume, gradually developed
much more elaborate apparatuses.

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:49.370
As well, here we have two editions
before kind of the transition

00:43:49.370 --> 00:43:54.410
between just the text of the core
and the surrounding commentary.

00:43:54.410 --> 00:44:00.450
So, we talk a little bit about how
the educational philosophy of --

00:44:00.450 --> 00:44:05.240
of contemporary academic
scholarship is somewhat different.

00:44:05.240 --> 00:44:10.990
I want to talk about two
other interesting things

00:44:10.990 --> 00:44:12.480
that are going on here.

00:44:12.480 --> 00:44:16.640
The first is that another
thing that the Bomberg edition

00:44:16.640 --> 00:44:21.040
of the Talmud did was to include,
in addition to the page itself,

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:26.220
several commentaries printed
independently in the back.

00:44:26.220 --> 00:44:28.830
He included Maimonides
Commentary of the Mishnah.

00:44:28.830 --> 00:44:30.130
He included the commentary

00:44:30.130 --> 00:44:36.120 position:56%
of the Rush Rabino Asher
[phonetic], the Spanish commentator.

00:44:36.120 --> 00:44:41.840
And, so he's kind of expanding --
it may not be on the page itself,

00:44:41.840 --> 00:44:44.770
but they're still there
in the volume.

00:44:44.770 --> 00:44:49.010
But, I want to point to
one thing in his inclusion

00:44:49.010 --> 00:44:52.560
of Maimonides Commentary
of the Mishnah,

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:54.770
that involved not publishing
Maimonides Commentary

00:44:54.770 --> 00:44:56.070
of the Mishnah.

00:44:56.070 --> 00:44:58.990 position:56%
But, by publishing a translation
into Hebrew of Maimonides Commentary

00:44:58.990 --> 00:45:05.080 position:56%
of the Mishnah, which was originally
published in Judeo -- or --

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:08.610
printed in a -- appeared in
manuscript in Judeo-Arabic,

00:45:08.610 --> 00:45:13.270
which was the vernacular at the
time that Maimonides was writing,

00:45:13.270 --> 00:45:15.950
or the place -- time and place
that Maimonides was writing.

00:45:15.950 --> 00:45:18.490
So, some of this just kind
of create this dialog,

00:45:18.490 --> 00:45:21.610
to create this conversation
on the page

00:45:21.610 --> 00:45:24.390
and in the volume and
with the students.

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:28.080
Part of that involves reworking --

00:45:28.080 --> 00:45:33.900
doing some work with the original
texts in order to enable them

00:45:33.900 --> 00:45:37.140
to be part of this conversation,
because in Venice there were --

00:45:37.140 --> 00:45:41.240
or the publications were not meant
